  </section>
  
<section id="fs-id1427157" class="section-summary"><title>Section Summary</title><list id="fs-id1972775"><item id="import-auto-id1170614029780">A simple circuit <emphasis effect="italics">is</emphasis> one in which there is a single voltage source and a single resistance.</item>

        <item id="import-auto-id1170614029788">One statement of Ohm’s law gives the relationship between current
<m:math>
 
  <m:mi>I</m:mi>
 
</m:math>,
voltage
<m:math>
 
  <m:mi>V</m:mi>
 
</m:math>,
and resistance
<m:math>
 
  <m:mi>R</m:mi>
 
</m:math>
in a simple circuit to be
<m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>I</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mi>V</m:mi><m:mi>R</m:mi></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mo>.</m:mo><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:math></item>

        <item id="import-auto-id1170614063028">Resistance has units of ohms (<m:math>
 
  <m:mtext>Ω</m:mtext>
 
</m:math>), related to volts and amperes by <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1 Ω</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mtext> 1 V/A</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>.</item>

        <item id="import-auto-id1170614028560">There is a voltage or <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>IR</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:math> drop across a resistor, caused by the current flowing through it, given by <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>V</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>IR</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>.</item>
        </list></section><section id="fs-id3232941" class="conceptual-questions" type="conceptual-questions"><title>Conceptual Questions</title>
            <exercise id="fs-id3008822" type="conceptual-questions"><problem id="fs-id3357131">
        <para id="import-auto-id1170614063336">The <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>IR</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:math> drop across a resistor means that there is a change in potential or voltage across the resistor. Is there any change in current as it passes through a resistor? Explain.</para>
        </problem></exercise>

            <exercise id="fs-id2392111" type="conceptual-questions"><problem id="fs-id3209349">
        <para id="import-auto-id1170614063516">How is the <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>IR</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:math> drop in a resistor similar to the pressure drop in a fluid flowing through a pipe?</para>
        </problem></exercise>
</section>

        <section id="fs-id3108374" type="problems-exercises" class="problems-exercises">
            <title>Problems &amp; Exercises</title>
        <exercise id="fs-id3045633" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2672096">
            <para id="import-auto-id1170614063082">What current flows through the bulb of a 3.00-V flashlight when its hot resistance is <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>60 Ω</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>?</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id1824260">
        <para id="import-auto-id1170614063148">0.833 A</para>
        </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise id="fs-id3154491" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2655753">
            <para id="import-auto-id1170614063157">Calculate the effective resistance of a pocket calculator that has a 1.35-V battery and through which 0.200 mA flows.</para>
        </problem></exercise>

        <exercise id="fs-id3172806" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1427809">
            <para id="import-auto-id1170614063464">What is the effective resistance of a car’s starter motor when 150 A flows through it as the car battery applies 11.0 V to the motor?</para>
        </problem>
<solution id="fs-id1368860">
        <para id="import-auto-id1170614063470"><m:math>
                
                    <m:mrow>

                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mrow>
                                    <m:mn>7</m:mn>
                                    <m:mtext>.</m:mtext>
                                    <m:mtext>33</m:mtext>
                                    <m:mi>×</m:mi>
                                    <m:msup>
                                        <m:mtext>10</m:mtext>

                                            <m:mrow>
                                                <m:mrow>
                                                    <m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo>
                                                    <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                                                </m:mrow>
                                            </m:mrow>

                                    </m:msup><m:mspace width="0.25em"/>
